<p>The Harvard Educational Records System (HERS) controls all non-financial data for Harvard College and the Graduate School of Arts and Sciences. After 20 years of operation, the system still managed enrollment of thousands of students, and had evolved into more than 300,000 lines of C code in hundreds of applications and thousands of shell scripts. New queries could force a HERS-savvy programmer to spend weeks building a custom script or C application. Changing fields could take months. And only a handful of experienced staff knew the system comprehensively.

<p><font class="sectionTitleText">Requirements</font>

<p>To overcome these limitations, Harvard needed an alternative that was platform-agnostic, extensible, absolutely secure, able to be integrated with many legacy applications and, above all, easy to maintain. Since users are scattered throughout academic departments, administration, housing and faculty, the HERS-2 system also had to be simple to master&#8212;a particularly important requirement once the application was opened to students and faculty. The deadline for accomplishing all this? The system had to be online in time to deliver the spring course catalog&#8212;due out in just six months.

<p><font class="sectionTitleText">Nevo's Solution</font>

<p>The diversity of users dictated a web-based solution, while the complexity of existing applications and the need to support legacy systems pointed to a three-tiered architecture with distributed business objects. A distributed Java solution therefore offered the best chance for long-term viability, even though it was still considered bleeding-edge technology at the time the project was initiated. Mitigating this risk, however, was the design objective that HERS-1 be integrated directly into HERS-2, thus eliminating the chance of disaster when it came time to make the transition to the new system.

<p>The assignment was broken into six modules, the first of which was to manage all information relating to courses and faculty. Among other things, Nevo was able to deliver the software used to produce the 800-page <i>Courses of Instruction</i> just four months after coding began, and to complete the entire assignment in only two-and-a-half years. Nevo's web-based solution has scaled successfully to 15,000 users in final deployment, and allows quick incorporation of outside systems such as a new security module. This plug-in capability is expected to keep HERS-2 running smoothly for at least another 20 years.
